                                "text": "Doudna"
                            }
                        ],
                        "given": [
                            {
                                "type": "text",
                                "text": "Jennifer A"
                            }
                        ]
                    }
                ],
                "abstract": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "text": "CRISPR-Cas9 genome editing is widely used for research and therapeutic  applications, but off-target activity remains a critical safety concern. Here we present cryo-electron microscopy structures of Cas9 bound to mismatched guide RNA-DNA duplexes, revealing the structural mechanisms underlying tolerance of mismatches at different positions. Our structures show that mismatches distal to the PAM are accommodated through local distortions, whereas PAM-proximal mismatches destabilise the R-loop and prevent HNH domain repositioning. These findings provide a structural framework for understanding Cas9 fidelity and guide rational engineering of high-fidelity variants."
                    }
                ],
