                            }
                        ],
                        "given": [
                            {
                                "type": "text",
                                "text": "James Z"
                            }
                        ]
                    },
                    {
                        "family": [
                            {
                                "type": "text",
                                "text": "Manson"
                            }
                        ],
                        "given": [
                            {
                                "type": "text",
                                "text": "JoAnn E"
                            }
                        ]
                    }
                ],
                "abstract": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "text": "IMPORTANCE: Whether high-dose vitamin D supplementation reduces all-cause  mortality remains uncertain despite numerous randomized clinical trials. OBJECTIVE: To examine the association between high-dose vitamin D supplementation and all-cause mortality. DATA SOURCES: MEDLINE, Embase, Cochrane Central Register of Controlled Trials, and ClinicalTrials.gov searched from inception to August 2023. STUDY SELECTION: Randomized clinical trials comparing high-dose vitamin D supplementation with lower doses or placebo in adults. DATA EXTRACTION AND SYNTHESIS: Two independent reviewers extracted data and assessed risk of bias. MAIN OUTCOMES AND MEASURES: All-cause mortality was the primary outcome. RESULTS: Fifty-three trials enrolling 94 148 participants were included. High-dose vitamin D did not reduce all-cause mortality compared with controls (relative risk, 0.97; 95% CI, 0.93-1.02; P = .23). CONCLUSIONS AND RELEVANCE: High-dose vitamin D supplementation does not appear to reduce all-cause mortality."
                    }
                ],
