                ],
                "abstract": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "text": "Antibody-drug conjugates (ADCs) represent a rapidly evolving class of  targeted therapeutics that combine the specificity of monoclonal antibodies with the cytotoxic potency of small-molecule drugs. Recent approvals of multiple ADCs across a broad range of tumour types have validated this approach and invigorated the field. Here we review the principles of ADC design, mechanisms of action and resistance, and the latest clinical data for approved and late-stage ADCs. We also discuss emerging strategies to enhance therapeutic windows and expand indications, including novel linker chemistry, site-specific conjugation and combination approaches."
                    }
