                ],
                "abstract": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "text": "IMPORTANCE: Long COVID, also known as post-acute sequelae of SARS-CoV-2  infection, affects a substantial proportion of individuals following acute COVID-19. OBJECTIVE: To estimate the prevalence of long COVID symptoms and associated complications. DESIGN, SETTING, AND PARTICIPANTS: Cross-sectional study using electronic health records from a large integrated health system. EXPOSURES: Laboratory-confirmed COVID-19 diagnosis between March 2020 and December 2021. MAIN OUTCOMES AND MEASURES: Presence of long COVID symptoms 4 or more weeks after infection. RESULTS: Among 9764 patients with COVID-19, 30.1% reported at least one long COVID symptom. The most common symptoms were fatigue (18.7%), dyspnea (14.2%), and cognitive impairment (7.8%). CONCLUSIONS AND RELEVANCE: Long COVID affects a significant proportion of patients and warrants ongoing clinical attention and research."
                    }
